E-hailing drivers across the country are planning to strike from Tuesday. Nkosinathi Zwane from Unity in Diversity E-Hailing Association spoke with eNCA's Tumelo Mothotoane about the planned industrial action. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - E-Hailing drivers across the country are planning a three-day shutdown. The Unity in Diversity E-hailing Association says its been calling on government to intervene and regulate the industry, yet nothing has been done. READ: Gauteng Transport MEC to meet with e-hailing drivers “The reality is that we’ve been in an abusive relationship with these app companies, they just do as they please when it comes to us," said Nkosinathia Zwane. "They call us partners but in reality, we do not understand the kind of relationship we have with them, every decision they make from taking prices down, to downgrading our cars, to drivers being blocked for minor offenses, they do not consult, there are no processes. WATCH: E-hailing strike | Drivers plan major shutdown "They just do as they please,  and our government has kept silent for far too long. "There is nothing that the government is doing, and that is why we will be embarking on an nation shut down on e-hailing from tomorrow [Tuesday] up-until Thursday.”